s==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{New Hampshire Wildcats football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1896 New Hampshire Wildcats football team}}\n[[Category:1896 college football season|New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:New Hampshire Wildcats football seasons]]\n[[Category:1896 in New Hampshire|New Hampshire Football]]\n", "name_user": "Dmoore5556", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSchedule:Andover, MA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1896_New_Hampshire_football_team"}
{"title_page": "Uno (Better Call Saul)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Uno (''Better Call Saul'')}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n|title        = Uno\n|series       = [[Better Call Saul]]\n|image        =\n|caption      =\n|season       = 1\n|episode      = 1\n|airdate      = {{Start date|2015|2|8}}\n|writer       = Vince Gilligan<br>[[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]]\n|director     = [[Vince Gilligan]]\n|music     = \"Address Unknown\" by [[The Ink Spots]]\n|length       = 53 minutes\n|guests       =\n* [[Julie Ann Emery]] as Betsy Kettleman\n* [[Jeremy Shamos]] as Craig Kettleman\n* [[M\u00edriam Col\u00f3n]] as Abuelita Salamanca\n* Eileen Fogarty as Mrs. Nguyen\n* Steven Levine as Lars Lindholm\n* Daniel Spenser Levine as Cal Lindholm\n* [[Raymond Cruz]] as [[List of Breaking Bad characters#Tuco Salamanca|Tuco Salamanca]]\n|prev         =\n|next         = [[Mijo]]\n|episode_list = List of Better Call Saul episodes\n| season_article = Better Call Saul (season 1)\n}}\n\"'''Uno'''\" is the [[series premiere]] of the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] television series ''[[Better Call Saul]]'', the spinoff series of ''[[Breaking Bad]]''. The episode aired on February 8, 2015, on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] in the United States. The episode was written by series creators [[Vince Gilligan]] and [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]], and directed by Gilligan. Outside of the United States, the episode premiered on streaming service [[Netflix]] in several countries. \n\nThe series mainly takes place in 2002, approximately six years prior to the title character [[Saul Goodman]] ([[Bob Odenkirk]]) meeting [[Walter White (Breaking Bad)|Walter White]] ([[Bryan Cranston]]). In \"Uno\", Jimmy McGill (Saul), is a struggling lawyer working at the back of a nail salon. [[Jonathan Banks]] also reprises his role as [[Mike Ehrmantraut]], a retired cop working as a parking lot security guard. The episode received generally positive reviews from critics, and it also broke the record for being the most-watched series premiere for a scripted series in U.S. cable history at the time, with 6.9 million viewers.<ref name=\"cablerecord\">{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/09/the-walking-dead-returns-to-15-6-million-viewers-better-call-saul-is-biggest-series-premiere-in-cable-history/361195/ |title='The Walking Dead' Returns to 15.6 Million Viewers + 'Better Call Saul' is Biggest Series Premiere in Cable History |last=Kondolojy |first=Amanda |date=February 9, 2015 |website=[[TV by the Numbers]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210011146/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/09/the-walking-dead-returns-to-15-6-million-viewers-better-call-saul-is-biggest-series-premiere-in-cable-history/361195/ |archive-date=February 10, 2015 |access-date=February 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n===Opening===\n[[Saul Goodman]], now going by the name \"Gene\", is managing a [[Cinnabon]] at a shopping mall in [[Omaha, Nebraska]]. He has grown a mustache and is balding. He suspects that a customer recognizes him, but this proves to be incorrect. In his apartment that night, Saul watches a [[VHS]] tape of his old television advertisements.\n\n===Main story===\nIn May 2002, James Morgan \"Jimmy\" McGill is a struggling [[public defender]] in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]]. He's representing three teenagers and tries to convince a jury that their actions were merely \"boys being boys\". In response, the prosecutor plays a video the teenagers made of them breaking into a morgue and having sex with a severed head. Afterwards, Jimmy complains about being paid too little for the defense. He gets a call from a prospective client, to whom he pretends to be his own mild-mannered Irish secretary. On his way out of the parking lot, Jimmy is stopped by [[Mike Ehrmantraut]], the parking lot attendant, who refuses to let him exit without either a payment or a court-supplied parking sticker.\n\nLater that day, Jimmy meets at a diner with the prospective clients, county treasurer Craig Kettleman and his wife, Betsy, who are being investigated for the disappearance of county funds. They are hesitant to hire Jimmy, and when later trying to order them flowers while driving, Jimmy hits a man on a skateboard. The skateboarder's twin brother records the incident on a video camera and threatens to call the police unless Jimmy pays them hush money. Recognizing their ruse, Jimmy refuses to pay and kicks the \"victim\". Afterwards, he returns to his \"office\" \u2013 the boiler room of a Vietnamese beauty salon. In the mail, he finds a check for $26,000 from Hamlin, Hamlin & McGill (HHM), his brother Chuck's law firm, which he proceeds to tear into several pieces. Jimmy confronts the partners, accusing them of trying to cheat Chuck out of his rightful share of the partnership. On his way out of the HHM office, he sees the Kettlemans going in, which causes him to become agitated over losing a potentially lucrative client.\n\nJimmy visits Chuck, who has had a mental breakdown and believes he has [[electromagnetic hypersensitivity]]. He requires visitors to leave their remote car door-opening keys and cellular phones in his mailbox and [[Ground (electricity)|ground themselves]] before entering his house. He has no working lights or refrigerator and works from home by lantern on a manual typewriter. Chuck refuses a buyout and also suggests that Jimmy stop using the name \"McGill\" for his personal firm to avoid public confusion with HHM. Jimmy tracks down the two skateboarders, Cal and Lars Lindholm, and suggests a partnership, telling them how he got the nickname \"Slippin' Jimmy\" as a young man by faking \"[[slip and fall]]s\" to get easy money. He arranges for one to be hit by a car driven by Betsy Kettleman, which will enable him to make another pitch to defend the Kettlemans on the embezzlement charge.  Instead of stopping to check Cal's status after hitting him, the motorist just [[hit and run|drives off]]. Cal and Lars give chase, but when the car stops, an elderly Hispanic woman exits. They try to get her to pay and follow her into her house. Jimmy arrives moments later to try and save them, trying to get in by referring to himself accurately but misleadingly as an \"[[officer of the court]]\", but is pulled into the house at gunpoint by [[Tuco Salamanca]].\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Vince Gilligan by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Series co-creator [[Vince Gilligan]], who also created predecessor ''[[Breaking Bad]]'']]\n\nIn July 2012, ''Breaking Bad'' creator [[Vince Gilligan]] hinted at a possible spin-off series focusing on Goodman.<ref name=\"comic-con interview\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/07/comic-con-qa-vince-gilligan-on-breaking-bad/ |title=Comic-Con Q&A: Vince Gilligan on 'Breaking Bad' |date=July 15, 2012 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002050559/http://www.deadline.com/2012/07/comic-con-qa-vince-gilligan-on-breaking-bad/ |archive-date=October 2, 2013 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>  In April 2013, the series was confirmed to be in development by Gilligan and Gould; the latter wrote the ''Breaking Bad'' episode that introduced the character.<ref name=\"deadline2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/04/breaking-bad-spinoff-series-bob-odenkirk-saul-goodman-amc/ |title=AMC Eyes 'Breaking Bad' Spinoff Toplined By Bob Odenkirk |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=April 9, 2013 |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140619103751/http://www.deadline.com/2013/04/breaking-bad-spinoff-series-bob-odenkirk-saul-goodman-amc/ |archive-date=June 19, 2014 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> In a July 2012 interview, Gilligan said he liked \"the idea of a lawyer show in which the main lawyer will do anything it takes to stay out of a court of law\" including settling on the courthouse steps.<ref name=\"deadline\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/09/breaking-bad-saul-goodman-spinoff-amc-series |title='Breaking Bad' Saul Goodman Spinoff A Go At AMC, Will Serve As Prequel To Original |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=September 11, 2013 |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810235809/http://www.deadline.com/2013/09/breaking-bad-saul-goodman-spinoff-amc-series/ |archive-date=August 10, 2014 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nThe show is filmed in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], where ''Breaking Bad'' was also shot.<ref name=\"filming\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2014/06/02/breaking-bad-prequel-better-call-saul-begins-filming-in-albuquerque-nm-today/ |title='Breaking Bad' prequel 'Better Call Saul' begins filming in Albuquerque, NM today! |date=June 2, 2014 |publisher=On Location Vacations |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220004814/http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2014/06/02/breaking-bad-prequel-better-call-saul-begins-filming-in-albuquerque-nm-today/ |archive-date=February 20, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> As filming began on June 2, 2014,<ref name=\"avclubfilming\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.avclub.com/article/its-time-begin-overanalyzing-first-better-call-sau-205338 |title=It's time to begin overanalyzing the first ''Better Call Saul'' set photos |last=O'Neal |first=Sean |date=June 3, 2014 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |publisher=[[The Onion]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211101918/http://www.avclub.com/article/its-time-begin-overanalyzing-first-better-call-sau-205338 |archive-date=February 11, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> concerns were expressed regarding the possible disappointment from the series' turnout, in terms of audience reception.<ref name=\"disappointment\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/03/breaking-bad-spinoff-better-call-sail_n_5439788.html |title=Vince Gilligan Admits His 'Breaking Bad' Spinoff Might Be A Mistake |last=Toomer |first=Jessica |date=June 3, 2014 |website=[[HuffPost]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219053013/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/03/breaking-bad-spinoff-better-call-sail_n_5439788.html |archive-date=February 19, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"moviefone\">{{Cite web |url=http://news.moviefone.com/2014/06/03/vince-gilligan-better-call-saul-mistake/ |title=Vince Gilligan Says 'Better Call Saul' Might Be a 'Mistake' |last=Roberts |first=Katie |date=June 3, 2014 |publisher=[[Moviefone]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606233510/http://news.moviefone.com/2014/06/03/vince-gilligan-better-call-saul-mistake/ |archive-date=June 6, 2014 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> On June 19, 2014, AMC announced it had renewed the series for a second season of 13 episodes to premiere in early 2016, with the first season to consist of 10 episodes, and that the series premiere had been delayed to early 2015.<ref name=\"numbers\">{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/06/19/amc-releases-first-photo-from-better-call-saul/275154/ |title='Better Call Saul' Renewed for Second Season by AMC; First Season Pushed Back to 2015 |last=Kondolojy |first=Amanda |date=June 19, 2014 |website=TV by the Numbers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212032900/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/06/19/amc-releases-first-photo-from-better-call-saul/275154/ |archive-date=February 12, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> The first teaser trailer debuted on AMC on August 10, 2014, and confirmed its premiere date of February 2015.<ref name=\"independent\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/better-call-saul-first-teaser-trailer-shows-younger-saul-confirms-release-date-9660693.html |title=Better Call Saul: First teaser trailer shows younger Saul, confirms release date |last=Hooten |first=Christopher |date=August 11, 2014 |website=[[The Independent]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141206053919/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/better-call-saul-first-teaser-trailer-shows-younger-saul-confirms-release-date-9660693.html |archive-date=December 6, 2014 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the opening scene from the episode, Saul (now hiding his real identity under the Gene Takavic alias), is working at a Nebraska [[Cinnabon]]. This scene is set in [[Omaha]], but it was filmed in Albuquerque, New Mexico, at the [[Cottonwood Mall (Albuquerque, New Mexico)|Cottonwood Mall]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newscastic.com/news/the-11-most-iconic-abq-locations-from-better-call-saul-season-1-2664760/ |title=The 11 Most Iconic ABQ Locations From 'Better Call Saul' Season 1 |date=April 7, 2015 |website=NewsCastic |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626075239/https://www.newscastic.com/news/the-11-most-iconic-abq-locations-from-better-call-saul-season-1-2664760/ |archive-date=June 26, 2017 |access-date=August 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\nThe episode received generally positive reviews and exceeded expectations. Erik Kain of ''[[Forbes]]'' said of the episode and series: \"[It] isn't just a spin-off of a popular TV show. So far, it's a terrific TV show on its own merits. It covers familiar ground, but it still manages to be its own unique snowflake.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2015/02/08/five-reasons-you-need-to-watch-better-call-saul/ |title=Five Reasons You Need To Watch 'Better Call Saul' |last=Kain |first=Erik |date=February 8, 2015 |website=[[Forbes]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209050031/http://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2015/02/08/five-reasons-you-need-to-watch-better-call-saul/ |archive-date=February 9, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> Hank Stuever of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' graded it a \"B+\" and wrote the series \"is right in line with the tone and style of the original, now-classic series\" and that it \"raises more questions in two hours than it will readily answer\".<ref name=\"washington post\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/entertainment/2015-midseason-tv-preview/#better-call-saul |title=Midseason TV 2015: Better Call Saul |last=Stuever |first=Hank |date=January 13, 2015 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116065600/http://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/entertainment/2015-midseason-tv-preview/#better-call-saul |archive-date=January 16, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> Stephen Marche of ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' wrote that the first few episodes were better than ''Breaking Bad''.<ref name=\"esq\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/culture/better-call-saul-review |title=Better Call Saul Review: The Last Hurrah of Difficult Men |last=Marche |first=Stephen |date=January 21, 2015 |website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207062730/http://www.esquire.com/blogs/culture/better-call-saul-review |archive-date=February 7, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> Kirsten Acuna of ''[[Business Insider]]'' declared the initial episodes \"everything you could possibly want from a spinoff television series\".<ref name=\"bi\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/better-call-saul-review-2015-1 |title=''Breaking Bad'' Fans Will Love ''Better Call Saul'' |last=Acuna |first=Kirsten |date=January 21, 2015 |website=[[Business Insider]] |publisher=Business Insider Inc. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208034220/http://www.businessinsider.com/better-call-saul-review-2015-1 |archive-date=February 8, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRoth Cornet of ''[[IGN]]'' gave the episode an 8.7 out of 10, saying \"Can Saul compete with Walter White? No. But he doesn't have to. ''Better Call Saul'' poses one simple, but fascinating question: What happened to Jimmy McGill that forced him to transform himself into the ruthless, hardened, yet entirely entertaining *criminal* lawyer Saul Goodman? The man that we came to know and love on ''Breaking Bad''. I, for one, look forward to watching that story unfold.\"<ref name=\"IGN\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/02/03/better-call-saul-uno-review |title=Better Call Saul: \"Uno\" Review |last=Cornet |first=Roth |date=February 2, 2015 |website=[[IGN]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207063444/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/02/03/better-call-saul-uno-review |archive-date=February 7, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMichael Star of The ''[[New York Post]]'' gave the episode a 3 out of 4 rating, saying:\n\n{{cquote|Sunday's premiere episode moves along at a brisk clip, with moody cinematography that, like ''Breaking Bad'', somehow makes the bright New Mexico sunlight, set against a brilliant azure sky, seem like stormy foreboding \u2014 lifted by Odenkirk\u2019s confident performance and Jimmy\u2019s snappy dialogue [...]. I'm always interested to see how/if a new show carries its premiere momentum forward, especially with a show like ''Better Call Saul'', which was hyped so relentlessly by AMC that you began to wonder.<ref name=\"nypost\">{{Cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2015/02/05/better-call-saul-hits-the-right-notes/ |title='Better Call Saul' hits the right notes |last=Starr |first=Michael |date=February 5, 2015 |website=[[New York Post]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208084153/http://nypost.com/2015/02/05/better-call-saul-hits-the-right-notes/ |archive-date=February 8, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nSome critics addressed skepticism prior to viewing the episode. Alessandra Stanley of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said \"It's common to dread a spinoff; some succeed, but plenty disappoint. There is absolutely no need to worry about this prequel to the ''Breaking Bad'' canon. ''Better Call Saul'' traces in loving, if corrosive, detail how Jimmy McGill, a debt-ridden, ambulance-chasing loser, changed his name to Saul Goodman and became a drug-lord [[consigliere]]. ''Better Call Saul'' is better than good: It\u2019s delightful \u2014 in a brutal, darkly comic way, of course.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/06/arts/television/better-call-saul-a-breaking-bad-spinoff-on-amc.html?_r=0 |title=Meth King's Lawyer: The Early Years |last=Stanley |first=Alessandra |date=February 5, 2015 |website=[[The New York Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207031030/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/06/arts/television/better-call-saul-a-breaking-bad-spinoff-on-amc.html?_r=0 |archive-date=February 7, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> Chris Jancelewicz of ''[[HuffPost]]'' gave the episode a highly favorable review despite his initial skepticism, saying: \"It is so good, right from the get-go, that I almost feel ashamed for ever doubting creator/writer Vince Gilligan, his writers, and lead actor Bob Odenkirk (Saul). ''Better Call Saul'' is a return to the tried-and-true New Mexico environment, the sweeping shots of wide-sky desert mixed with strip-mall extravagance, the lushness juxtaposed with the dark comedy, which, as it was with ''Breaking Bad'', both jarring and hilarious at the same time. You'll find yourself laughing in spite of yourself.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/chris-jancelewicz/better-call-saul-review-amc_b_6606030.html |title='Better Call Saul' Review: 'Breaking Bad' Fans Will Not Be Disappointed |last=Jancelewicz |first=Chriss |date=February 4, 2015 |website=HuffPost |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207065422/http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/chris-jancelewicz/better-call-saul-review-amc_b_6606030.html |archive-date=February 7, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRobert Bianco of ''[[USA Today]]'' said \"Face it: When AMC announced it had ordered a prequel to ''Breaking Bad'', odds are many of us saw it as a callow move by a network bereft of new ideas to milk an old one for all it was worth. Well, we were right \u2014 but what we failed to factor in were the gifts star Bob Odenkirk and creators Vince Gilligan and Peter Gould would bring to ''Better Call Saul'' [...] and their ability to transform what looked to be a sow's ear into something pretty much approaching a silk purse.\"<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2015/02/05/better-call-saul-review/22921741/ |title='Better Call Saul' does right by 'Bad' |last=Bianco |first=Robert |date=February 6, 2015 |website=[[USA Today]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208083055/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2015/02/05/better-call-saul-review/22921741/ |archive-date=February 8, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> He ultimately gave the episode a 3.5 rating out of 4.<ref name=usatoday/> One of few negative reviews came from Tony Wong of The ''[[Toronto Star]]'', saying \"It is beautifully and lovingly shot. It is funny and it is dark. But it's a lot to ask Bob Odenkirk to carry the show without help.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2015/02/06/better-call-saul-a-prequel-no-one-asked-for-review.html |title=Better Call Saul a prequel no one asked for: review |last=Wong |first=Tony |date=February 6, 2015 |website=[[Toronto Star]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208105625/http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2015/02/06/better-call-saul-a-prequel-no-one-asked-for-review.html |archive-date=February 8, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn her review of the series premiere, Mary McNamara of The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' summarized that \"the beauty of Saul was his unflappable nature; no matter how dire or dreadful the circumstances, he was able to identify the next logical step and take it. Jimmy McGill doesn't know how to do that yet; ''Better Call Saul'' will show us how he learned.\"<ref name=\"latimesreview\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-better-call-saul-review-20150207-column.html |title=Review: 'Better Call Saul' the real deal, and Odenkirk delivers goods |last=McNamara |first=Mary |date=February 6, 2015 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209012654/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-better-call-saul-review-20150207-column.html |archive-date=February 9, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings and accolades===\nUpon airing, the episode became the highest-rated series premiere for a scripted series in U.S. cable history up to that date, with 6.9 million viewers.<ref name=cablerecord/> The show placed second for the night among U.S. cable networks, behind only its lead-in show ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]'', which as of February 9, 2015, ranks as the second-highest rated entertainment broadcast with adults 18\u201349 in the U.S., behind ''[[The Blacklist (TV series)|The Blacklist]]'' episode \"[[Luther Braxton]]\" which aired after [[Super Bowl XLIX]].<ref name=cablerecord/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/02/post-super-bowl-episode-of-the-blacklist-scores-as-primetimes-top-broadcast-entertainment-telecast-since-the-oscars/358527/ |title=Post Super Bowl Episode of 'The Blacklist' Scores as Primetime's Top Broadcast Entertainment Telecast Since the Oscars |last=Bibel |first=Sara |date=February 2, 2015 |website=TV by the Numbers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209132944/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/02/post-super-bowl-episode-of-the-blacklist-scores-as-primetimes-top-broadcast-entertainment-telecast-since-the-oscars/358527/ |archive-date=February 9, 2015 |access-date=February 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/03/sunday-final-ratings-the-blacklist-adjusted-down-final-super-bowl-numbers/358679/ |title=Sunday Final Ratings: 'The Blacklist' Adjusted Down & Final Super Bowl Numbers |last=Bibel |first=Sara |date=February 3, 2015 |website=TV by the Numbers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208073841/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/03/sunday-final-ratings-the-blacklist-adjusted-down-final-super-bowl-numbers/358679/ |archive-date=February 8, 2015 |access-date=February 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nVince Gilligan and Peter Gould won the [[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Episodic Drama]] for this episode.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/wga-awards-winners-writers-guild-america-1201705269/ |title=WGA Honors 'Big Short,' 'Spotlight,' 'Mad Men' at 68th Awards |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=February 13, 2016 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503074029/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/wga-awards-winners-writers-guild-america-1201705269/ |archive-date=May 3, 2016 |access-date=February 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Television|United States}}\n* [http://www.amctv.com/shows/better-call-saul/episodes/season-1/uno \"Uno\"] at [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]\n* {{imdb episode|3464768|Uno}}\n\n{{Better Call Saul}}\n{{WritersGuildofAmericaEpisodicDramaScreenplay 2010s}}\n\n[[Category:American television pilots]]\n[[Category:Better Call Saul (season 1) episodes]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Peter Gould (writer)]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Vince Gilligan]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Uno (''Better Call Saul'')}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n|title        = Uno\n|series       = [[Better Call Saul]]\n|image        = \n|caption      = \n|season       = 1\n|episode      = 1\n|airdate      = {{Start date|2015|2|8}}\n|writer       = Vince Gilligan<br>[[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]]\n|director     = [[Vince Gilligan]]\n|music     = \"Address Unknown\" by [[The Ink Spots]]\n|length       = 53 minutes\n|guests       =\n*[[Julie Ann Emery]] as Betsy Kettleman\n*[[Jeremy Shamos]] as Craig Kettleman\n*[[M\u00edriam Col\u00f3n]] as Abuelita Salamanca\n*Eileen Fogarty as Mrs. Nguyen\n*Steven Levine as Lars Lindholm\n*Daniel Spenser Levine as Cal Lindholm\n*[[Raymond Cruz]] as [[List of Breaking Bad characters#Tuco Salamanca|Tuco Salamanca]]\n|prev         = \n|next         = [[Mijo]]\n|episode_list = List of Better Call Saul episodes\n| season_article = Better Call Saul (season 1)\n}}\n\"'''Uno'''\" is the [[series premiere]] of the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] television series ''[[Better Call Saul]]'', the spinoff series of ''[[Breaking Bad]]''. The episode aired on February 8, 2015, on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] in the United States. The episode was written by series creators [[Vince Gilligan]] and [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]], and directed by Gilligan. Outside of the United States, the episode premiered on streaming service [[Netflix]] in several countries.  \n\nThe series mainly takes place in 2002, approximately six years prior to the title character [[Saul Goodman]] ([[Bob Odenkirk]]) meeting [[Walter White (Breaking Bad)|Walter White]] ([[Bryan Cranston]]). In \"Uno\", Jimmy McGill (Saul), is a struggling lawyer working at the back of a nail salon. [[Jonathan Banks]] also reprises his role as [[Mike Ehrmantraut]], a retired cop working as a parking lot security guard. The episode received generally positive reviews from critics, and it also broke the record for being the most-watched series premiere for a scripted series in U.S. cable history at the time, with 6.9 million viewers.<ref name=\"cablerecord\">{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/09/the-walking-dead-returns-to-15-6-million-viewers-better-call-saul-is-biggest-series-premiere-in-cable-history/361195/ |title='The Walking Dead' Returns to 15.6 Million Viewers + 'Better Call Saul' is Biggest Series Premiere in Cable History |last=Kondolojy |first=Amanda |date=February 9, 2015 |website=[[TV by the Numbers]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210011146/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/09/the-walking-dead-returns-to-15-6-million-viewers-better-call-saul-is-biggest-series-premiere-in-cable-history/361195/ |archive-date=February 10, 2015 |access-date=February 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n===Opening===\n[[Saul Goodman]], now going by the name \"Gene\", is managing a [[Cinnabon]] at a shopping mall in [[Omaha, Nebraska]]. He has grown a mustache and is balding. He suspects that a customer recognizes him, but this proves to be incorrect. In his apartment that night, Saul watches a [[VHS]] tape of his old television advertisements.\n\n===Main story===\nIn May 2002, James Morgan \"Jimmy\" McGill is a struggling [[public defender]] in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]]. He's representing three teenagers and tries to convince a jury that their actions were merely \"boys being boys\". In response, the prosecutor plays a video the teenagers made of them breaking into a morgue and having sex with a severed head. Afterwards, Jimmy complains about being paid too little for the defense. He gets a call from a prospective client, to whom he pretends to be his own mild-mannered Irish secretary. On his way out of the parking lot, Jimmy is stopped by [[Mike Ehrmantraut]], the parking lot attendant, who refuses to let him exit without either a payment or a court-supplied parking sticker.\n\nLater that day, Jimmy meets at a diner with the prospective clients, county treasurer Craig Kettleman and his wife, Betsy, who are being investigated for the disappearance of county funds. They are hesitant to hire Jimmy, and when later trying to order them flowers while driving, Jimmy hits a man on a skateboard. The skateboarder's twin brother records the incident on a video camera and threatens to call the police unless Jimmy pays them hush money. Recognizing their ruse, Jimmy refuses to pay and kicks the \"victim\". Afterwards, he returns to his \"office\" \u2013 the boiler room of a Vietnamese beauty salon. In the mail, he finds a check for $26,000 from Hamlin, Hamlin & McGill (HHM), his brother Chuck's law firm, which he proceeds to tear into several pieces. Jimmy confronts the partners, accusing them of trying to cheat Chuck out of his rightful share of the partnership. On his way out of the HHM office, he sees the Kettlemans going in, which causes him to become agitated over losing a potentially lucrative client.\n\nJimmy visits Chuck, who has had a mental breakdown and believes he has [[electromagnetic hypersensitivity]]. He requires visitors to leave their remote car door-opening keys and cellular phones in his mailbox and [[Ground (electricity)|ground themselves]] before entering his house. He has no working lights or refrigerator and works from home by lantern on a manual typewriter. Chuck refuses a buyout and also suggests that Jimmy stop using the name \"McGill\" for his personal firm to avoid public confusion with HHM. Jimmy tracks down the two skateboarders, Cal and Lars Lindholm, and suggests a partnership, telling them how he got the nickname \"Slippin' Jimmy\" as a young man by faking \"[[slip and fall]]s\" to get easy money. He arranges for one to be hit by a car driven by Betsy Kettleman, which will enable him to make another pitch to defend the Kettlemans on the embezzlement charge.  Instead of stopping to check Cal's status after hitting him, the motorist just [[hit and run|drives off]]. Cal and Lars give chase, but when the car stops, an elderly Hispanic woman exits. They try to get her to pay and follow her into her house. Jimmy arrives moments later to try and save them, trying to get in by referring to himself accurately but misleadingly as an \"[[officer of the court]]\", but is pulled into the house at gunpoint by [[Tuco Salamanca]].\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Vince Gilligan by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Series co-creator [[Vince Gilligan]], who also created predecessor ''[[Breaking Bad]]'']]\n\nIn July 2012, ''Breaking Bad'' creator [[Vince Gilligan]] hinted at a possible spin-off series focusing on Goodman.<ref name=\"comic-con interview\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/07/comic-con-qa-vince-gilligan-on-breaking-bad/ |title=Comic-Con Q&A: Vince Gilligan on 'Breaking Bad' |date=July 15, 2012 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002050559/http://www.deadline.com/2012/07/comic-con-qa-vince-gilligan-on-breaking-bad/ |archive-date=October 2, 2013 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>  In April 2013, the series was confirmed to be in development by Gilligan and Gould; the latter wrote the ''Breaking Bad'' episode that introduced the character.<ref name=\"deadline2\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/04/breaking-bad-spinoff-series-bob-odenkirk-saul-goodman-amc/ |title=AMC Eyes 'Breaking Bad' Spinoff Toplined By Bob Odenkirk |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=April 9, 2013 |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140619103751/http://www.deadline.com/2013/04/breaking-bad-spinoff-series-bob-odenkirk-saul-goodman-amc/ |archive-date=June 19, 2014 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> In a July 2012 interview, Gilligan said he liked \"the idea of a lawyer show in which the main lawyer will do anything it takes to stay out of a court of law\" including settling on the courthouse steps.<ref name=\"deadline\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/09/breaking-bad-saul-goodman-spinoff-amc-series |title='Breaking Bad' Saul Goodman Spinoff A Go At AMC, Will Serve As Prequel To Original |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=September 11, 2013 |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810235809/http://www.deadline.com/2013/09/breaking-bad-saul-goodman-spinoff-amc-series/ |archive-date=August 10, 2014 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nThe show is filmed in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], where ''Breaking Bad'' was also shot.<ref name=\"filming\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2014/06/02/breaking-bad-prequel-better-call-saul-begins-filming-in-albuquerque-nm-today/ |title='Breaking Bad' prequel 'Better Call Saul' begins filming in Albuquerque, NM today! |date=June 2, 2014 |publisher=On Location Vacations |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220004814/http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2014/06/02/breaking-bad-prequel-better-call-saul-begins-filming-in-albuquerque-nm-today/ |archive-date=February 20, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> As filming began on June 2, 2014,<ref name=\"avclubfilming\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.avclub.com/article/its-time-begin-overanalyzing-first-better-call-sau-205338 |title=It's time to begin overanalyzing the first ''Better Call Saul'' set photos |last=O'Neal |first=Sean |date=June 3, 2014 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |publisher=[[The Onion]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211101918/http://www.avclub.com/article/its-time-begin-overanalyzing-first-better-call-sau-205338 |archive-date=February 11, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> concerns were expressed regarding the possible disappointment from the series' turnout, in terms of audience reception.<ref name=\"disappointment\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/03/breaking-bad-spinoff-better-call-sail_n_5439788.html |title=Vince Gilligan Admits His 'Breaking Bad' Spinoff Might Be A Mistake |last=Toomer |first=Jessica |date=June 3, 2014 |website=[[HuffPost]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219053013/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/06/03/breaking-bad-spinoff-better-call-sail_n_5439788.html |archive-date=February 19, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"moviefone\">{{Cite web |url=http://news.moviefone.com/2014/06/03/vince-gilligan-better-call-saul-mistake/ |title=Vince Gilligan Says 'Better Call Saul' Might Be a 'Mistake' |last=Roberts |first=Katie |date=June 3, 2014 |publisher=[[Moviefone]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606233510/http://news.moviefone.com/2014/06/03/vince-gilligan-better-call-saul-mistake/ |archive-date=June 6, 2014 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> On June 19, 2014, AMC announced it had renewed the series for a second season of 13 episodes to premiere in early 2016, with the first season to consist of 10 episodes, and that the series premiere had been delayed to early 2015.<ref name=\"numbers\">{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/06/19/amc-releases-first-photo-from-better-call-saul/275154/ |title='Better Call Saul' Renewed for Second Season by AMC; First Season Pushed Back to 2015 |last=Kondolojy |first=Amanda |date=June 19, 2014 |website=TV by the Numbers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212032900/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/06/19/amc-releases-first-photo-from-better-call-saul/275154/ |archive-date=February 12, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> The first teaser trailer debuted on AMC on August 10, 2014, and confirmed its premiere date of February 2015.<ref name=\"independent\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/better-call-saul-first-teaser-trailer-shows-younger-saul-confirms-release-date-9660693.html |title=Better Call Saul: First teaser trailer shows younger Saul, confirms release date |last=Hooten |first=Christopher |date=August 11, 2014 |website=[[The Independent]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141206053919/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/better-call-saul-first-teaser-trailer-shows-younger-saul-confirms-release-date-9660693.html |archive-date=December 6, 2014 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the opening scene from the episode, Saul (now hiding his real identity under the Gene Takavic alias), is working at a Nebraska [[Cinnabon]]. This scene is set in [[Omaha]], but it was filmed in Albuquerque, New Mexico, at the [[Cottonwood Mall (Albuquerque, New Mexico)|Cottonwood Mall]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newscastic.com/news/the-11-most-iconic-abq-locations-from-better-call-saul-season-1-2664760/ |title=The 11 Most Iconic ABQ Locations From 'Better Call Saul' Season 1 |date=April 7, 2015 |website=NewsCastic |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626075239/https://www.newscastic.com/news/the-11-most-iconic-abq-locations-from-better-call-saul-season-1-2664760/ |archive-date=June 26, 2017 |access-date=August 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\nThe episode received generally positive reviews and exceeded expectations. Erik Kain of ''[[Forbes]]'' said of the episode and series: \"[It] isn't just a spin-off of a popular TV show. So far, it's a terrific TV show on its own merits. It covers familiar ground, but it still manages to be its own unique snowflake.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2015/02/08/five-reasons-you-need-to-watch-better-call-saul/ |title=Five Reasons You Need To Watch 'Better Call Saul' |last=Kain |first=Erik |date=February 8, 2015 |website=[[Forbes]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209050031/http://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2015/02/08/five-reasons-you-need-to-watch-better-call-saul/ |archive-date=February 9, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> Hank Stuever of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' graded it a \"B+\" and wrote the series \"is right in line with the tone and style of the original, now-classic series\" and that it \"raises more questions in two hours than it will readily answer\".<ref name=\"washington post\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/entertainment/2015-midseason-tv-preview/#better-call-saul |title=Midseason TV 2015: Better Call Saul |last=Stuever |first=Hank |date=January 13, 2015 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116065600/http://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/entertainment/2015-midseason-tv-preview/#better-call-saul |archive-date=January 16, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> Stephen Marche of ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' wrote that the first few episodes were better than ''Breaking Bad''.<ref name=\"esq\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/culture/better-call-saul-review |title=Better Call Saul Review: The Last Hurrah of Difficult Men |last=Marche |first=Stephen |date=January 21, 2015 |website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |publisher=[[Hearst Magazines]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207062730/http://www.esquire.com/blogs/culture/better-call-saul-review |archive-date=February 7, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> Kirsten Acuna of ''[[Business Insider]]'' declared the initial episodes \"everything you could possibly want from a spinoff television series\".<ref name=\"bi\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/better-call-saul-review-2015-1 |title=''Breaking Bad'' Fans Will Love ''Better Call Saul'' |last=Acuna |first=Kirsten |date=January 21, 2015 |website=[[Business Insider]] |publisher=Business Insider Inc. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208034220/http://www.businessinsider.com/better-call-saul-review-2015-1 |archive-date=February 8, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRoth Cornet of ''[[IGN]]'' gave the episode an 8.7 out of 10, saying \"Can Saul compete with Walter White? No. But he doesn't have to. ''Better Call Saul'' poses one simple, but fascinating question: What happened to Jimmy McGill that forced him to transform himself into the ruthless, hardened, yet entirely entertaining *criminal* lawyer Saul Goodman? The man that we came to know and love on ''Breaking Bad''. I, for one, look forward to watching that story unfold.\"<ref name=\"IGN\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/02/03/better-call-saul-uno-review |title=Better Call Saul: \"Uno\" Review |last=Cornet |first=Roth |date=February 2, 2015 |website=[[IGN]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207063444/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/02/03/better-call-saul-uno-review |archive-date=February 7, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMichael Star of The ''[[New York Post]]'' gave the episode a 3 out of 4 rating, saying:\n\n{{cquote|Sunday's premiere episode moves along at a brisk clip, with moody cinematography that, like ''Breaking Bad'', somehow makes the bright New Mexico sunlight, set against a brilliant azure sky, seem like stormy foreboding \u2014 lifted by Odenkirk\u2019s confident performance and Jimmy\u2019s snappy dialogue [...]. I'm always interested to see how/if a new show carries its premiere momentum forward, especially with a show like ''Better Call Saul'', which was hyped so relentlessly by AMC that you began to wonder.<ref name=\"nypost\">{{Cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2015/02/05/better-call-saul-hits-the-right-notes/ |title='Better Call Saul' hits the right notes |last=Starr |first=Michael |date=February 5, 2015 |website=[[New York Post]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208084153/http://nypost.com/2015/02/05/better-call-saul-hits-the-right-notes/ |archive-date=February 8, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nSome critics addressed skepticism prior to viewing the episode. Alessandra Stanley of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said \"It's common to dread a spinoff; some succeed, but plenty disappoint. There is absolutely no need to worry about this prequel to the ''Breaking Bad'' canon. ''Better Call Saul'' traces in loving, if corrosive, detail how Jimmy McGill, a debt-ridden, ambulance-chasing loser, changed his name to Saul Goodman and became a drug-lord [[consigliere]]. ''Better Call Saul'' is better than good: It\u2019s delightful \u2014 in a brutal, darkly comic way, of course.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/06/arts/television/better-call-saul-a-breaking-bad-spinoff-on-amc.html?_r=0 |title=Meth King's Lawyer: The Early Years |last=Stanley |first=Alessandra |date=February 5, 2015 |website=[[The New York Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207031030/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/06/arts/television/better-call-saul-a-breaking-bad-spinoff-on-amc.html?_r=0 |archive-date=February 7, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> Chris Jancelewicz of ''[[HuffPost]]'' gave the episode a highly favorable review despite his initial skepticism, saying: \"It is so good, right from the get-go, that I almost feel ashamed for ever doubting creator/writer Vince Gilligan, his writers, and lead actor Bob Odenkirk (Saul). ''Better Call Saul'' is a return to the tried-and-true New Mexico environment, the sweeping shots of wide-sky desert mixed with strip-mall extravagance, the lushness juxtaposed with the dark comedy, which, as it was with ''Breaking Bad'', both jarring and hilarious at the same time. You'll find yourself laughing in spite of yourself.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/chris-jancelewicz/better-call-saul-review-amc_b_6606030.html |title='Better Call Saul' Review: 'Breaking Bad' Fans Will Not Be Disappointed |last=Jancelewicz |first=Chriss |date=February 4, 2015 |website=HuffPost |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207065422/http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/chris-jancelewicz/better-call-saul-review-amc_b_6606030.html |archive-date=February 7, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRobert Bianco of ''[[USA Today]]'' said \"Face it: When AMC announced it had ordered a prequel to ''Breaking Bad'', odds are many of us saw it as a callow move by a network bereft of new ideas to milk an old one for all it was worth. Well, we were right \u2014 but what we failed to factor in were the gifts star Bob Odenkirk and creators Vince Gilligan and Peter Gould would bring to ''Better Call Saul'' [...] and their ability to transform what looked to be a sow's ear into something pretty much approaching a silk purse.\"<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2015/02/05/better-call-saul-review/22921741/ |title='Better Call Saul' does right by 'Bad' |last=Bianco |first=Robert |date=February 6, 2015 |website=[[USA Today]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208083055/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2015/02/05/better-call-saul-review/22921741/ |archive-date=February 8, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> He ultimately gave the episode a 3.5 rating out of 4.<ref name=usatoday/> One of few negative reviews came from Tony Wong of The ''[[Toronto Star]]'', saying \"It is beautifully and lovingly shot. It is funny and it is dark. But it's a lot to ask Bob Odenkirk to carry the show without help.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2015/02/06/better-call-saul-a-prequel-no-one-asked-for-review.html |title=Better Call Saul a prequel no one asked for: review |last=Wong |first=Tony |date=February 6, 2015 |website=[[Toronto Star]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208105625/http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2015/02/06/better-call-saul-a-prequel-no-one-asked-for-review.html |archive-date=February 8, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn her review of the series premiere, Mary McNamara of The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' summarized that \"the beauty of Saul was his unflappable nature; no matter how dire or dreadful the circumstances, he was able to identify the next logical step and take it. Jimmy McGill doesn't know how to do that yet; ''Better Call Saul'' will show us how he learned.\"<ref name=\"latimesreview\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-better-call-saul-review-20150207-column.html |title=Review: 'Better Call Saul' the real deal, and Odenkirk delivers goods |last=McNamara |first=Mary |date=February 6, 2015 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209012654/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-better-call-saul-review-20150207-column.html |archive-date=February 9, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings and accolades===\nUpon airing, the episode became the highest-rated series premiere for a scripted series in U.S. cable history up to that date, with 6.9 million viewers.<ref name=cablerecord/> The show placed second for the night among U.S. cable networks, behind only its lead-in show ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]'', which as of February 9, 2015, ranks as the second-highest rated entertainment broadcast with adults 18\u201349 in the U.S., behind ''[[The Blacklist (TV series)|The Blacklist]]'' episode \"[[Luther Braxton]]\" which aired after [[Super Bowl XLIX]].<ref name=cablerecord/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/02/post-super-bowl-episode-of-the-blacklist-scores-as-primetimes-top-broadcast-entertainment-telecast-since-the-oscars/358527/ |title=Post Super Bowl Episode of 'The Blacklist' Scores as Primetime's Top Broadcast Entertainment Telecast Since the Oscars |last=Bibel |first=Sara |date=February 2, 2015 |website=TV by the Numbers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209132944/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/02/post-super-bowl-episode-of-the-blacklist-scores-as-primetimes-top-broadcast-entertainment-telecast-since-the-oscars/358527/ |archive-date=February 9, 2015 |access-date=February 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/03/sunday-final-ratings-the-blacklist-adjusted-down-final-super-bowl-numbers/358679/ |title=Sunday Final Ratings: 'The Blacklist' Adjusted Down & Final Super Bowl Numbers |last=Bibel |first=Sara |date=February 3, 2015 |website=TV by the Numbers |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208073841/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/02/03/sunday-final-ratings-the-blacklist-adjusted-down-final-super-bowl-numbers/358679/ |archive-date=February 8, 2015 |access-date=February 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nVince Gilligan and Peter Gould won the [[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: Episodic Drama]] for this episode.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/wga-awards-winners-writers-guild-america-1201705269/ |title=WGA Honors 'Big Short,' 'Spotlight,' 'Mad Men' at 68th Awards |last=McNary |first=Dave |date=February 13, 2016 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503074029/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/wga-awards-winners-writers-guild-america-1201705269/ |archive-date=May 3, 2016 |access-date=February 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Television|United States}}\n*[http://www.amctv.com/shows/better-call-saul/episodes/season-1/uno \"Uno\"] at [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]\n*{{imdb episode|3464768|Uno}}\n\n{{Better Call Saul}}\n{{WritersGuildofAmericaEpisodicDramaScreenplay 2010s}}\n\n[[Category:American television pilots]]\n[[Category:Better Call Saul (season 1) episodes]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Peter Gould (writer)]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Vince Gilligan]]\n", "name_user": "SacredDragonX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uno_(Better_Call_Saul)"}
{"title_page": "Suji ka Halwa", "text_new": "{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Sajjige\n| image            = File:Sooji Halwa (Rava Sheera).jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = \n| alternate_name   = Lapsi(Gujarati),Sheera, sooji halwa\n| country          = India\n| region           = Indian subcontinent\n| creator          = \n| type             = Indian desserts, Breakfast\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[semolina]], [[sugar]], [[ghee]], [[milk]]\n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n\n'''Sajjige''', as it is called in parts of Tulunadu, is a highly heralded as a sweet dish. Semolina, when made sweet, is called '''sheero'''. Several variants of this dish are available under other names in various parts of India. For instance, in [[Maharashtra]], it is called sheera which is the sweet version and in [[North India]] it is called '''sooji (suji) halwa''' or '''Mohan bhog'''. Sometimes also referred to as sheero, this dish is generally made and served on auspicious hindu holidays, as well as momentous celebrations. It is also served in [[Europe]] and United States as [[semolina]] [[pudding]]. \n\nSajjige is a [[Cuisine of India]] and a kesar/saffron-flavoured variation of this is the [[Kesari sheera]]. Sajjige is served as a breakfast or a dessert item. The normal variety though is unflavoured and prepared with just [[semolina]], [[sugar]], [[ghee]], and [[milk]].\n\nAs it is easy to prepare, it is often favoured as a breakfast item, especially with pooris, in other parts of India. This dish is known to have several health benefits.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Historical usage==\nIn Medieval Arab cuisine, semolina was cooked with water, honey, camphor, saffron, and sesame oil.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rondinson|first=Maxime  |title=Medieval Arab Cookery, essays and translations |year=1998 |publisher=Prospect Books | pages = 423\u2013424|display-authors=etal|id={{ASIN|0907325912|country=uk}} }}</ref>\n\nIn 14th-century Spain, semolina was cooked with almond milk, oil and optionally saffron for coloring.<ref>{{cite book|last=Santanach |first=Joan   |title=The Book of Sent Sovi: Medieval recipes from Catalonia |year=2008 |publisher=Tamesis Books |asin=1855661640 | pages = }}</ref>\n\nIn England circa 1845, baked semolina puddings were recommended by renowned cooks such as [[Eliza Acton]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Acton|first=Eliza|title=Modern Cookery for Private Families}}</ref>\nCurrently semolina is a traditional sweet in Bangladesh called '''Suji Halwa'''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kesari bhath]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{Cuisine of India}}\n\n[[Category:Vegetarian dishes of India]]\n[[Category:Indian desserts]]\n[[Category:South Indian cuisine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Sajjige\n| image            = File:Sooji Halwa (Rava Sheera).jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = \n| alternate_name   = Lapsi(Gujarati),Sheera, sooji halwa\n| country          = India\n| region           = Indian subcontinent\n| creator          = \n| type             = Indian desserts, Breakfast\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[semolina]], [[sugar]], [[ghee]], [[milk]]\n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n\n'''Sajjige''', as it is called in parts of Tulunadu, is a highly heralded as a sweet dish. Semolina, when made sweet, is called '''sheera'''. Several variants of this dish are available under other names in various parts of India. For instance, in [[Maharashtra]], it is called sheera which is the sweet version and in [[North India]] it is called '''sooji (suji) halwa''' or '''Mohan bhog'''. It is also served in [[Europe]] and United States as [[semolina]] [[pudding]]. It was first brought into India by the [[Arabs]], and was adopted as a number of Indian varieties.{{Citation Needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nSajjige is a [[Cuisine of India]] and a kesar/saffron-flavoured variation of this is the [[Kesari sheera]]. Sajjige is served as a breakfast or a dessert item. The normal variety though is unflavoured and prepared with just [[semolina]], [[sugar]], [[ghee]], and [[milk]].\n\nAs it is easy to prepare, it is often favoured as a breakfast item, especially with pooris, in other parts of India. This dish is known to have several health benefits.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Historical usage==\nIn Medieval Arab cuisine, semolina was cooked with water, honey, camphor, saffron, and sesame oil.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rondinson|first=Maxime  |title=Medieval Arab Cookery, essays and translations |year=1998 |publisher=Prospect Books | pages = 423\u2013424|display-authors=etal|id={{ASIN|0907325912|country=uk}} }}</ref>\n\nIn 14th-century Spain, semolina was cooked with almond milk, oil and optionally saffron for coloring.<ref>{{cite book|last=Santanach |first=Joan   |title=The Book of Sent Sovi: Medieval recipes from Catalonia |year=2008 |publisher=Tamesis Books |asin=1855661640 | pages = }}</ref>\n\nIn England circa 1845, baked semolina puddings were recommended by renowned cooks such as [[Eliza Acton]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Acton|first=Eliza|title=Modern Cookery for Private Families}}</ref>\nCurrently semolina is a traditional sweet in Bangladesh called '''Suji Halwa'''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kesari bhath]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{Cuisine of India}}\n\n[[Category:Vegetarian dishes of India]]\n[[Category:Indian desserts]]\n[[Category:South Indian cuisine]]\n", "name_user": "67.85.228.150", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suji_ka_Halwa"}
{"title_page": "2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n|year = 2017\n|team = Alabama Crimson Tide\n|sport=football\n|logo = Alabama Crimson Tide logo.svg\n|logo_size = 130px\n|logo_alt = Alabama Crimson\n|record = 13\u20131\n|conf_record = 7\u20131\n|conference = Southeastern Conference\n|division = Western Division\n|short_conf = SEC\n|CoachRank = 1\n|APRank = 1\n|head_coach = [[Nick Saban]]\n|hc_year= 11th\n|off_coach = [[Brian Daboll]]\n|oc_year=  1st\n|cooff_coach1 = [[Mike Locksley]]\n|cooc1_year = 1st as co-OC; 2nd overall \n|def_coach = [[Jeremy Pruitt]]\n|dc_year= 2nd as DC; 9th overall\n|codef_coach1 = [[Tosh Lupoi]]\n|codc1_year = 1st as co-DC; 3rd overall\n|off_scheme = Multiple\n|def_scheme = [[3\u20134 defense|3\u20134]]\n|captain = [[Minkah Fitzpatrick]]<br>[[Rashaan Evans]]<br>[[Shaun Dion Hamilton]]<br>[[Bradley Bozeman]]\n|stadium = [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]]<br>(Capacity: 101,821)\n|champion= Consensus national champion<br>SEC Western Division co-champion<br>Sugar Bowl champion\n|bowl = [[2018 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]] (CFP Semifinal)\n|bowl_result = W 24\u20136 vs. [[2017 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]]<br>[[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship|CFP National Championship]]<br/> W 26\u201323 <sup>OT</sup> vs. [[2017 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]]\n}}\n{{2017 SEC football standings}}\nThe '''2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team''' represented the [[University of Alabama]] during the [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. This season marked the Crimson Tide's 125th overall season, its 84th as a member of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) and its 26th within the SEC [[Southeastern Conference#Current members|Western Division]]. They played their home games at [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]] in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama]] and were led by eleventh-year head coach [[Nick Saban]].\n\nAlabama ended the season as consensus [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|national champions]] by winning their second [[College Football Playoff]] national championship. This was their 17th claimed national title in school history, and fifth under head coach Nick Saban.\n\nAlabama, coming off a national title game loss to [[2016 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]] in [[2016 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2016]], began the year ranked first in the [[AP Poll]]. The team opened the year with a victory over then-No. 3 [[2017 Florida State Seminoles football team|Florida State]] in the [[Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game]], which was the highest ranked season-opening match-up in the history of the AP Poll.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2017/08/31/college-football-week-1-theres-no-better-kickoff-than-alabama-florida-state/|title=College football Week 1 TV schedule: Alabama vs. Florida State is a pretty, pretty good kickoff|date=September 2, 2017|first=Matt|last=Bonesteel|newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Alabama won their first 11 games convincingly, but fell on the road to rival [[2017 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] in the regular season finale, and since the two teams were tied atop the SEC West Division at 7\u20131, Auburn advanced to the [[2017 SEC Championship Game]] on the head-to-head tiebreaker. Alabama fell to number six in the rankings leading up to conference championship weekend. In the final [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football rankings|College Football Playoff rankings]] of the year, 11\u20131 Alabama  controversially rose to number four after sitting idle, ahead of 12\u20131 [[2017 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]], 11\u20132 [[Big Ten Conference]] champion [[2017 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] and 12\u20130 [[American Athletic Conference]] champion [[2017 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]. This earned Alabama a place in the national semi-final to be played at the [[2018 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]] against first-seeded [[2017 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]], the third consecutive playoff meeting between the two schools. Alabama won by a score of 24\u20136 and advanced to the [[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship]] against SEC champion [[2017 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]]. The Crimson Tide pulled off a dramatic come-from-behind overtime victory to win the game 26\u201323 and the national title.\n\nAlabama's offense was led by sophomore quarterback [[Jalen Hurts]], who finished with 2,081 passing yards, 17 passing touchdowns and just one interception. He added 855 rushing yards and 8 rushing touchdowns on the ground. Freshman quarterback [[Tua Tagovailoa]] served as the backup and was named game MVP of the national championship game after Hurts was benched at halftime. Running back [[Damien Harris]] led the rushing attack with exactly 1,000 rushing yards and 11 touchdowns on the year. Wide receiver [[Calvin Ridley]] and offensive tackle [[Jonah Williams]] were named [[2017 All-SEC football team|first-team All-SEC]]. The Crimson Tide defense, which led the country in scoring and yards allowed, was led by [[2017 College Football All-America Team|consensus first-team All-American]] and [[Chuck Bednarik Award]]-winning safety [[Minkah Fitzpatrick]]. He was joined on the All-SEC first team by defensive tackles [[Daron Payne]] and [[Raekwon Davis]], linebacker [[Rashaan Evans]], and safety [[Ronnie Harrison]].\n\n== Previous season and offseason ==\n{{Main|2016 Alabama Crimson Tide football team}}\n\nIn 2016, Alabama came into the season ranked No. 1 in both preseason polls and finished the regular season 13\u20130, 8\u20130 SEC. The Crimson Tide were ranked number one the entire season prior to their national championship appearance against [[2016 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]]. Alabama won the Western Division of SEC and qualified to play in the [[2016 SEC Championship Game]] against the [[2016 Florida Gators football team|Florida Gators]]. Alabama defeated the Gators again in the rematch from the previous year's SEC Championship 54\u201316 in Atlanta, Georgia, clinching the program's 26th SEC title. As the No. 1 seed in the third season of the [[College Football Playoff]], the Crimson Tide were selected to play in the semifinal game at the [[2016 Peach Bowl]] against No. 4 [[2016 Washington Huskies football team|Washington]] of the [[Pac-12 Conference]]. Alabama beat the Huskies 24\u20137, advancing them to the [[2017 College Football Playoff National Championship]] Game against No. 2 Clemson of the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]]. The Crimson Tide lost to the Tigers in the rematch from the previous year's College Football Playoff National Championship 35\u201331 after [[Deshaun Watson]] threw the game-winning TD pass to [[Hunter Renfrow]] with :01 left. The Crimson Tide finished the 2016 season with a record of 14\u20131.\n\n===Departures===\nThe Crimson Tide lost twenty-three senior football players to graduation, another four players to the NFL Draft, and four more players from the 2016 team due to various other reasons.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\"\n! colspan=\"8\" |Offseason departures\n|-\n! Name !! Number !! Pos. !! Height !! Weight !! Year !! Hometown !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| [[Jonathan Allen]] || #93 || DE || 6'3 || 291  || Senior || [[Leesburg, Virginia|Leesburg, VA]] || Graduated\n|-\n| [[Ryan Anderson (American football)|Ryan Anderson]] || #22 || LB || 6'2 || 253 || RS Senior  || [[Daphne, Alabama|Daphne, AL]] || Graduated\n|-\n| [[OJ Howard|O.J. Howard]] || #88 || TE || 6'6 || 251 || Senior || [[Prattville, Alabama|Prattville, AL]] || Graduated\n|-\n| Truett Harris || #86 || TE || 6'3 || 235 || Senior || [[Brentwood, Tennessee|Brentwood, TN]] || Graduated\n|-\n| Brandon Moore || #17 || OL || 6'0 || 248 || Senior || [[Cinc