}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style={{CollegePrimaryStyle|Alabama Crimson Tide|color=white}} | Player\n! style={{CollegePrimaryStyle|Alabama Crimson Tide|color=white}} | Position\t\n! style={{CollegePrimaryStyle|Alabama Crimson Tide|color=white}} | Round\t\n! style={{CollegePrimaryStyle|Alabama Crimson Tide|color=white}} | Overall Pick \n! style={{CollegePrimaryStyle|Alabama Crimson Tide|color=white}} | NFL Team\n|-\n| [[Minkah Fitzpatrick]] || S || 1 || 11 || [[Miami Dolphins]]\n|-\n| [[Daron Payne]] || DT || 1 || 13 || [[Washington Redskins]]\n|-\n| [[Rashaan Evans]] || LB || 1 || 22 || [[Tennessee Titans]]\n|-\n| [[Calvin Ridley]] || WR || 1 || 26 || [[Atlanta Falcons]]\n|-\n| [[Ronnie Harrison]] || S || 3 || 93 || [[Jacksonville Jaguars]]\n|-\n| [[Da'Shawn Hand]] || DE || 4 || 114 || [[Detroit Lions]]\n|-\n| [[Anthony Averett]] || CB || 4 || 118 || [[Baltimore Ravens]]\n|-\n| [[JK Scott]] || P || 5 || 172 || [[Green Bay Packers]]\n|-\n| [[Shaun Dion Hamilton]] || LB || 6 || 197 || Washington Redskins\n|-\n| [[Bradley Bozeman]] || C || 6 || 215 || Baltimore Ravens\n|-\n| [[Bo Scarbrough]] || RB || 7 || 236 || [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n|-\n| [[Joshua Frazier]] || DT || 7 || 246 || [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n|-\n| [[Robert Foster (American football)|Robert Foster]] || WR || Undrafted || &nbsp; || [[Buffalo Bills]]\n|-\n| [[Levi Wallace (American football)|Levi Wallace]] || CB || Undrafted || &nbsp; || Buffalo Bills\n|-\n| [[Tony Brown (defensive back, born 1995)|Tony Brown]]|| CB || Undrafted || &nbsp; || [[Los Angeles Chargers]]\n|-\n| [[J. C. Hassenauer]] || C || Undrafted || &nbsp; || Atlanta Falcons\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{Alabama Crimson Tide football}}\n{{College football national champion (championship game era) navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2017 Alabama Crimson Tide Football Team}}\n[[Category:2017 Southeastern Conference football season|Alabama]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football seasons]]\n[[Category:College Football Playoff National Champions]]\n[[Category:Sugar Bowl champion seasons]]\n[[Category:2017 in sports in Alabama|Alabama Crimson Tide football team]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n|year = 2017\n|team = Alabama Crimson Tide\n|sport=football\n|logo = Alabama Crimson Tide logo.svg\n|logo_size = 130px\n|logo_alt = Alabama Crimson\n|record = 13\u20131\n|conf_record = 7\u20131\n|conference = Southeastern Conference\n|division = Western Division\n|short_conf = SEC\n|CoachRank = 1\n|APRank = 1\n|head_coach = [[Nick Saban]]\n|hc_year= 11th\n|off_coach = [[Brian Daboll]]\n|oc_year=  1st\n|cooff_coach1 = [[Mike Locksley]]\n|cooc1_year = 1st as co-OC; 2nd overall \n|def_coach = [[Jeremy Pruitt]]\n|dc_year= 2nd as DC; 9th overall\n|codef_coach1 = [[Tosh Lupoi]]\n|codc1_year = 1st as co-DC; 3rd overall\n|off_scheme = Multiple\n|def_scheme = [[3\u20134 defense|3\u20134]]\n|captain = [[Minkah Fitzpatrick]]<br>[[Rashaan Evans]]<br>[[Shaun Dion Hamilton]]<br>[[Bradley Bozeman]]\n|stadium = [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]]<br>(Capacity: 101,821)\n|champion= Consensus national champion<br>SEC Western Division co-champion<br>Sugar Bowl champion\n|bowl = [[2018 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]] (CFP Semifinal)\n|bowl_result = W 24\u20136 vs. [[2017 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]]<br>[[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship|CFP National Championship]]<br/> W 26\u201323 <sup>OT</sup> vs. [[2017 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]]\n}}\n{{2017 SEC football standings}}\nThe '''2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team''' represented the [[University of Alabama]] during the [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. This season marked the Crimson Tide's 125th overall season, its 84th as a member of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) and its 26th within the SEC [[Southeastern Conference#Current members|Western Division]]. They played their home games at [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]] in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama]] and were led by eleventh-year head coach [[Nick Saban]].\n\nAlabama ended the season as consensus [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|national champions]] by winning their second [[College Football Playoff]] national championship. This was their 17th claimed national title in school history, and fifth under head coach Nick Saban.\n\nAlabama, coming off a national title game loss to [[2016 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]] in [[2016 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2016]], began the year ranked first in the [[AP Poll]]. The team opened the year with a victory over then-No. 3 [[2017 Florida State Seminoles football team|Florida State]] in the [[Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game]], which was the highest ranked season-opening match-up in the history of the AP Poll.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2017/08/31/college-football-week-1-theres-no-better-kickoff-than-alabama-florida-state/|title=College football Week 1 TV schedule: Alabama vs. Florida State is a pretty, pretty good kickoff|date=September 2, 2017|first=Matt|last=Bonesteel|newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref> Alabama won their first 11 games convincingly, but fell on the road to rival [[2017 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] in the regular season finale, and since the two teams were tied atop the SEC West Division at 7\u20131, Auburn advanced to the [[2017 SEC Championship Game]] on the head-to-head tiebreaker. Alabama fell to number six in the rankings leading up to conference championship weekend. In the final [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football rankings|College Football Playoff rankings]] of the year, 11\u20131 Alabama  controversially rose to number four after sitting idle, ahead of 12\u20131 [[2017 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]], 11\u20132 [[Big Ten Conference]] champion [[2017 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] and 12\u20130 [[American Athletic Conference]] champion [[2017 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]. This earned Alabama a place in the national semi-final to be played at the [[2018 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]] against first-seeded [[2017 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]], the third consecutive playoff meeting between the two schools. Alabama won by a score of 24\u20136 and advanced to the [[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship]] against SEC champion [[2017 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]]. The Crimson Tide pulled off a dramatic come-from-behind overtime victory to win the game 26\u201323 and the national title.\n\nAlabama's offense was led by sophomore quarterback [[Jalen Hurts]], who finished with 2,081 passing yards, 17 passing touchdowns and just one interception. He added 855 rushing yards and 8 rushing touchdowns on the ground. Freshman quarterback [[Tua Tagovailoa]] served as the backup and was named game MVP of the national championship game after Hurts was benched at halftime. Running back [[Damien Harris]] led the rushing attack with exactly 1,000 rushing yards and 11 touchdowns on the year. Wide receiver [[Calvin Ridley]] and offensive tackle [[Jonah Williams]] were named [[2017 All-SEC football team|first-team All-SEC]]. The Crimson Tide defense, which led the country in scoring and yards allowed, was led by [[2017 College Football All-America Team|consensus first-team All-American]] and [[Chuck Bednarik Award]]-winning safety [[Minkah Fitzpatrick]]. He was joined on the All-SEC first team by defensive tackles [[Daron Payne]] and [[Raekwon Davis]], linebacker [[Rashaan Evans]], and safety [[Ronnie Harrison]].\n\n== Previous season and offseason ==\n{{Main|2016 Alabama Crimson Tide football team}}\n\nIn 2016, Alabama came into the season ranked No. 1 in both preseason polls and finished the regular season 13\u20130, 8\u20130 SEC. The Crimson Tide were ranked number one the entire season prior to their national championship appearance against [[2016 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]]. Alabama won the Western Division of SEC and qualified to play in the [[2016 SEC Championship Game]] against the [[2016 Florida Gators football team|Florida Gators]]. Alabama defeated the Gators again in the rematch from the previous year's SEC Championship 54\u201316 in Atlanta, Georgia, clinching the program's 26th SEC title. As the No. 1 seed in the third season of the [[College Football Playoff]], the Crimson Tide were selected to play in the semifinal game at the [[2016 Peach Bowl]] against No. 4 [[2016 Washington Huskies football team|Washington]] of the [[Pac-12 Conference]]. Alabama beat the Huskies 24\u20137, advancing them to the [[2017 College Football Playoff National Championship]] Game against No. 2 Clemson of the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]]. The Crimson Tide lost to the Tigers in the rematch from the previous year's College Football Playoff National Championship 35\u201331 after [[Deshaun Watson]] threw the game-winning TD pass to [[Hunter Renfrow]] with :01 left. The Crimson Tide finished the 2016 season with a record of 14\u20131.\n\n===Departures===\nThe Crimson Tide lost twenty-three senior football players to graduation, another four players to the NFL Draft, and four more players from the 2016 team due to various other reasons.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\"\n! colspan=\"8\" |Offseason departures\n|-\n! Name !! Number !! Pos. !! Height !! Weight !! Year !! Hometown !! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| [[Jonathan Allen]] || #93 || DE || 6'3 || 291  || Senior || [[Leesburg, Virginia|Leesburg, VA]] || Graduated\n|-\n| [[Ryan Anderson (American football)|Ryan Anderson]] || #22 || LB || 6'2 || 253 || RS Senior  || [[Daphne, Alabama|Daphne, AL]] || Graduated\n|-\n| [[OJ Howard|O.J. Howard]] || #88 || TE || 6'6 || 251 || Senior || [[Prattville, Alabama|Prattville, AL]] || Graduated\n|-\n| Truett Harris || #86 || TE || 6'3 || 235 || Senior ||